Tenth Avenue, west side, north from West 20th to 21st Streets. Note at the extreme right, the tenement at the N. W. oorner of 21st Street. This was demolished and the ew Roman Catholic Church of the Guardiar Angel erected there. This organization was formerly located at No. 511-5 W. 23rd Street. Demolition of their church there, for the new New York Central Railroad elevated roadbed,necessitated this
Nnew structure.
March 3, 1929
July 28, 1931
P. L. Sperr

Tenth Avenue, west side, south from W. 20th Street, showing an open area between 19th and 17th Streets traversed by the raised road bed of the New York Central Railroad. Seen a cross same are the structures of the Merchants Refrigerating Company and the National Biscuit Company between 17th and 15th Streets. These are emphasized in No. 3. Note the diesel drawn train using the street bed. This feature has now been eliminated and such
trains run on the raised tracks seen in No. 1.
View No. 2 is similar to the preceding from a point slightly southward and shows demolition debris on the 19th to 18th Streets block front. Note also the Railroad yard between 18th
and 17th Streets.
June 14, 1938.
iews 253: July 16, 1932.
